                 <note>Huber’s reading implies an <foreign>akṣara</foreign> <foreign>u</foreign> before <foreign>ru</foreign>, but, despite the fact that the stone is a bit worn here, we can be certain that this is not what was written. The required initial <foreign>u</foreign> is apparently spelled, not with the akṣara <foreign>u</foreign>, but with <foreign>u</foreign>-vocalization below <foreign>akṣara</foreign> <foreign>a</foreign>. Such spellings are known in other parts of Southeast Asia, but this seems to be a unique case in Campā epigraphy.</note><!-- argr2sapi: I am now inclined to think we have -y u- with y as hiatus-breaking consonant; this is substandard usage, but not unparalleled in the world of Sanskrit literature, though I don't remember having seen a Campā case. -->
